### 2. Termination & Budget Limits (Critical Risk: Rapid Balance Drain & Stalls)

The model agent relies on step limits (`step <= steps`) and voluntary termination. Relying solely on these safeguards puts you at risk of several problems:

```
[Agent Turn] ──► [Hallucinates Invalid Path] ──► [Tool Fails with Error Text] ──► [Model Reacts with Same Path] ──► [Infinite Loop Code-Stall]
```

*   **Hallucinated Argument Stalls:** When a tool call fails because of an invalid parameter, the model often immediately retries the exact same call with identical arguments, expecting a different outcome. It can do this 10 to 16 times in seconds, burning through context window tokens.
*   **Ping-Pong Tool Loops:** Two tools can easily end up in a circular loop (for example, a command execution tool returns a compiler error, which triggers a search tool, which triggers the same command execution tool).
*   **The Cost of Deep Context Windows:** As shown below, without prompt caching, the token cost of a multi-turn tool loop grows quadratically ($O(N^2)$). If step 1 is 5,000 tokens of codebase context, step 10 can become over 50,000 tokens of payload data.

$$C_{\text{cumulative}} = \sum_{k=1}^{T} \left( I_{\text{system}} + I_{\text{tools}} + I_{\text{user}} + \sum_{j=1}^{k-1} (M_{\text{user}, j} + M_{\text{assistant}, j}) \right)$$

