       Current Bridge Request Payload
       {
         "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
         "system": "Plain text combined instructions block", // WRONG RAW PLAIN TEXT FORMAT
         "messages": [
            // Plain non-cached message loops
         ]
       }
```

These structural differences in system headers will cause compatibility issues. In particular, how Anthropic handles first-party system prompts versus how the local bridge structures billing headers can lead to authorization failures.

#### User Context Interception Limitations
The capture proxy implementation relies on intercepting OAuth token payloads:

```javascript
clientSocket.on('data', (data) => {
  // Try to capture auth from the first request in the tunnel
  if (ANTHROPIC_HOSTNAMES.has(hostname) && !ctx.interceptedToken) { ... }
});
```

This capture logic is limited:
* This pattern assumes all intercepted incoming requests fit within the first `8192` bytes of the stream buffer. If the client sends a massive initial header segment (e.g. containing large session cookies or detailed system path data), the auth-matching regex won't run, leaving calls unauthenticated.
* When local development tools run under different network setups (such as configured VPN paths or corporate proxies), traffic is routed elsewhere, bypassing localhost interception entirely.

#### Prompt Caching Integration Issues
Anthropic's prompt caching relies on precise, designated markers within system array elements:

```json
"cache_control": { "type": "ephemeral" }
```

In `src/runner/run.js`, caching parameters are set via:

```javascript
const cachedSystem = typeof system === 'string'
  ? [{ type: 'text', text: system, cache_control: { type: 'ephemeral' } }]
  : system.map((block) => ({ ...block, cache_control: { type: 'ephemeral' } }));
```

This caching strategy has a major problem:
If `system` is array-structured, the map function applies `cache_control` to **every single block**.

According to Anthropic's technical documentation, **a request can contain at most 4 cache control markers**.

If the system prompt array has more than 4 blocks, applying cache control to all of them will trigger a validation error, causing the API to reject the request with a `400 Bad Request` execution error.

```
       REJECTED REQUEST ARRAY STRUCTURING: System prompt has 5 blocks

         [Block 1] -> Cache Control Applied
         [Block 2] -> Cache Control Applied
         [Block 3] -> Cache Control Applied
         [Block 4] -> Cache Control Applied
         [Block 5] -> Cache Control Applied -- LIMIT EXCEEDED (Max 4 Cache Controls Allowed)

         RESULT: Upstream API returns 400 Bad Request immediately.
```

To resolve this, restructure your system array mapping to apply `cache_control` only to the last block, ensuring the dynamic payload is cached without exceeding the upstream limit:

```javascript
// Correctly structures cache milestones to comply with Anthropic limits
function applySystemCachePrecisely(systemPromptPayload) {
  if (typeof systemPromptPayload === 'string') {
    return [
      {
        type: 'text',
        text: systemPromptPayload,
        cache_control: { type: 'ephemeral' }
      }
    ];
  }

  if (Array.isArray(systemPromptPayload)) {
    // Only apply target caching to the final block of instructions
    return systemPromptPayload.map((block, idx) => {
      if (idx === systemPromptPayload.length - 1) {
        return { ...block, cache_control: { type: 'ephemeral' } };
      }
      // Return remaining blocks without cache controls
      const cleanedBlock = { ...block };
      delete cleanedBlock.cache_control;
      return cleanedBlock;
    });
  }
  return systemPromptPayload;
}
```

