# Architectural Critique & Risk Assessment: `claude-local-bridge` Local Runner

This is an aggressively clever architecture. Splitting the VS Code bridge (transport/OAuth/fingerprinting) from the Node runner (tool loop, persistence, safety) is the correct separation of concerns. The runner uses an iterative `for`-loop rather than recursion, which avoids stack overflows, and JSONL transcripts satisfy your flat-file constraint.

But moving the agent loop out of Anthropic's cloud and into a local Node process introduces real fragility. Below is a candid assessment, with concrete file references, exact commands, and—because you're new to terminals—explicit warnings about which actions are irreversible.

---

## Component Map (Blast-Radius Rating)

A quick mental model of where mistakes hurt the most:

| File | Role | Danger | Why it matters |
|---|---|:---:|---|
| `bin/local-bridge-runner.js` | CLI entrypoint, arg parsing, stdin, boots loop | 🟢 Low | Wrong flags here weaken every layer below. |
| `src/runner/run.js` | Agent loop, tool dispatch, transcript, budget math | 🔴 High | Bugs cause infinite loops, billing overruns, and resume corruption. |
| `src/runner/safety.js` | Path confinement & shell sanitization | 💀 Critical | A flaw here is *the* path to data loss / system file exposure. |
| `src/runner/tool-registry.js` | Tool catalog, read/write classification | 🟡 Medium | Mis-tagging a write tool as read-only bypasses confirmation. |
| `src/runner/permissions.js` | `--accept-edits`, `--allow-shell`, undo plumbing | 🟡 Medium | Currently has unused `undoLog` infrastructure (see §3). |
| `src/bridge/credentials.js` | OAuth header injection, billing header, system-prompt mutation | 🟡 Medium | Source of multiple Anthropic schema violations (§4). |
